ing tests don't import the internal classes. There are some limitations regarding reflection, so maybe I should stick to the documentation of grpc-java. There are also ambiguities about public vs. internal classes.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether to add a test for `InternalCheckGcpEnvironment.isOnGcp()`. It returns a boolean but it's tricky to assert the environment. I could check if it's stable between calls, as it reads a sys file under native conditions. Also, I might want to test `AltsChannelBuilder.forTarget` since existing tests only use `forAddress`. But does that make it too similar to what’s already covered? I need to be mindful not to duplicate tests, yet adding missing factory variants could be justified.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating service registration tests**\\\\n\\\\nI'm realizing that the existing tests for `AltsServerBuilder` cover forwarding options but not service registration or interceptors. Since the method is public, I could build and start a server to assert that `server.getServices()` includes the correct service after it starts. I don't need a client for this. However, I’m concerned about whether this test would duplicate the checks already in place, especially since it will inherently involve starting the server again. It might be a slight overlap.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_8jwx2IVseg1rEISXDJr7lm1p|fc_062a81f5b6aa58660169fd0ab666f08197ad2d8ae28cbd88b0\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"javap -classpath ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/io.grpc/grpc-api/1.71.0/*/grpc-api-1.71.0.jar -public io.grpc.Server | sed -n '1,120p'\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 849, \"output\": 1207, \"cacheRead\": 29184, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 31240, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\